lecell><italics><link><target>Council of Pisa</target><part>Pisa</part></link></italics></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell>14231429</tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Antipope Clement VIII</target><part>Clement VIII</part></link></tablecell><tablecell>Clemens</tablecell><tablecell>Gil Snchez Muoz</tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Avignon Papacy</target><part>Avignon</part></link></tablecell><tablecell rowspan="3"><link><target>Pope Martin V</target><part>Martin V</part></link></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell>14241429</tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Antipope Benedict XIV</target><part>Benedict XIV</part></link></tablecell><tablecell>Benedictus</tablecell><tablecell>Bernard Garnier</tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell>&amp;nbsp;</tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell>14301437</tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Antipope Benedict XIV</target><part>Benedict XIV</part></link></tablecell><tablecell>Benedictus</tablecell><tablecell>Jean Carrier</tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell>&amp;nbsp;</tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell rowspan="2">14391449</tablecell><tablecell rowspan="2"><link><target>Antipope Felix V</target><part>Felix V</part></link></tablecell><tablecell rowspan="2">Flix</tablecell><tablecell rowspan="2">Duke Amadeus VIII of Savoy</tablecell><tablecell rowspan="2"><link><target>Chambry</target></link>, Savoy</tablecell><tablecell rowspan="2">56/65 (67)</tablecell><tablecell rowspan="2">9 y, 5 m, 2 d</tablecell><tablecell rowspan="2">Elected by the<space/><link><target>Council of Florence</target><part>Council of Basel</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Pope Eugene IV</target><part>Eugene IV</part></link></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell rowspan="2"><link><target>Pope Nicholas V</target><part>Nicholas V</part></link></tablecell></tablerow></table><heading level='3'>Quasi-cardinal-nephews</heading><paragraph><template><target>Main</target><arg>List of cardinal-nephews</arg></template>Many antipopes created cardinals, known as<space/><italics>quasi-cardinals</italics>, and a few created<space/><link><target>cardinal-nephew</target><trail>s</trail></link>, known as<space/><italics>quasi-cardinal-nephews</italics>.</paragraph><table class="wikitable sortable" style="width:100%"><tablerow><tablehead width="10%">Quasi-cardinal</tablehead><tablehead width="11%">Nephew of</tablehead><tablehead width="10%">Elevated</tablehead><tablehead>width=&quot;*&quot; | Notes</tablehead></tablerow><tablerow valign="top"><tablecell><link><target>Giacomo Alberti</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Antipope Nicholas V</target></link></tablecell><tablecell>15 May 1328</tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Excommunicated</target></link><space/>by<space/><link><target>Pope John XXII</target></link>.<extension extension_name='ref' name="mxiv">Miranda, Salvador. 1998. &quot;<link type='external' href='http://www.fiu.edu/~mirandas/consistories-xiv.htm'>14th Century (13031404)</link>.&quot;</extension></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell><link><target>Amedeo Saluzzo</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Antipope Clement VII</target></link></tablecell><tablecell>23 December 1383</tablecell><tablecell>Abandoned<space/><link><target>Antipope Benedict XIII</target></link><space/>after having been deposed by him on 21 October 1408; participated in the<space/><link><target>Council of Pisa</target></link>, the election of<space/><link><target>Pope Alexander V</target></link><space/>(now regarded as an antipope), the<space/><link><target>Council of Constance</target></link>, and the conclave of<space/><link><target>Pope Martin V</target></link>.<extension extension_name='ref' name="mxiv"></extension></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell><link><target>Tommaso Brancaccio</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Antipope John XXIII</target></link></tablecell><tablecell>6 June 1411</tablecell><tablecell>Attended the<space/><link><target>Council of Constance</target></link>, and the conclave of<space/><link><target>Pope Martin V</target></link>.<extension extension_name='ref'>Miranda, Salvator. 1998. &quot;<link type='external' href='http://www.fiu.edu/~mirandas/bios1411.htm#Lando'>The Cardinals of the Holy Roman Church: Biographical Dictionary: Antipope&amp;#93; John XXIII (14101415): Consistory of 6 June 1411 (I)</link>.&quot;</extension></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell><link><target>Gil Snchez Muoz</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Antipope Clement VIII</target></link></tablecell><tablecell>26 July 1429</tablecell><tablecell>Submitted to<space/><link><target>Pope Martin V</target></link><space/>after his uncle abdicated.<extension extension_name='ref' name="mxv">Miranda, Salvador. 1998. &quot;<link type='external' href='http://www.fiu.edu/~mirandas/consistories-xv.htm'>15th Century (14041503)</link>.&quot;</extension></tablecell></tablerow></table><heading level='2'>Modern claimants to papacy</heading><paragraph><template><target>details</target><arg>Conclavism</arg></template></paragraph><paragraph>In modern times various people claim to be pope and, though they do not fit the technical definition of &quot;antipope&quot;, are sometimes referred to as such. They are usually leaders of<space/><link><target>sedevacantism</target><part>sedevacantist</part></link><space/>groups who view the See of Rome as vacant and elect someone to fill it. They are sometimes referred to as<space/><link><target>conclavism</target><part>conclavists</part></link><space/>because of their claim, on the basis of an election by a &quot;conclave&quot; of perhaps half a dozen laypeople, as in the case of<space/><link><target>David Bawden</target></link><space/>(&quot;Pope Michael I&quot;), to have rendered the See no longer vacant. A significant number of these have taken the name &quot;<link><target>Pope Peter II</target><part>Peter II</part></link>&quot;, owing to its special significance. From the point of view of the<space/><link><target>Roman Catholic Church</target></link>, they are<space/><link><target>schism (religion)</target><part>schismatics</part></link>, and as such are<space/><link><target>Latae sententiae</target><part>automatically excommunicated</part></link>.<extension extension_name='ref'><link type='external' href='http://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P52.HTM'>Code of Canon Law, canon 1364</link></extension></paragraph><heading level='3'>Collinites</heading><paragraph><template><target>details</target><arg>Apostles of Infinite Love</arg></template></paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Michel Collin (antipope)</target><part>Michel Collin or Colin</part></link><space/>(Pope Clement XV), self-proclaimed (19501974) in France, founder of Order of the Mother of God (a name later changed to Apostles of Infinite Love)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Jean-Gaston Tremblay</target></link>, Gregory XVII (19682011), in<space/><link><target>Canada</target></link></listitem></list><heading level='3'>Palmarian Catholic Church</heading><paragraph><template><target>details</target><arg>Palmarian Catholic Church</arg></template></paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Clemente Domnguez y Gmez</target></link><space/>(Pope Gregory XVII), mystically self-proclaimed (1978&amp;ndash;2005) in Spain</listitem><listitem><link><target>Manuel Corral</target></link><space/>(Pope Peter II) (2005&amp;ndash;11)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Sergio Mara</target></link><space/>(Pope Gregory XVIII) (2011&amp;ndash;present)</listitem></list><paragraph>The Palmarian Catholic Church regards<space/><link><target>Pope Paul VI</target></link>, whom they revere as a martyr, and his predecessors as true popes, but hold, on the grounds of claimed apparitions, that the Pope of Rome is excommunicated and that the position of the<space/><link><target>Holy See</target></link><space/>has, since 1978, been transferred to the See of<space/><link><target>El Palmar de Troya</target></link>.</paragraph><heading level='3'>Other examples</heading><paragraph>The following were elected by allegedly faithful Catholics, none of whom was a<space/><link><target>Cardinal (Catholicism)</target><part>cardinal</part></link>:</paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem>Popes of the &quot;<link><target>Legio Maria</target></link>&quot;, based in western<space/><link><target>Kenya</target></link><space/>(not technically Conclavist): Timothy Joseph Blasio Ahitler (19631998). Pius Lawrence Jairo Chiaji Adera (19982004). Raphael Titus Otieno (2004present).</listitem><listitem><link><target>David Bawden</target></link><space/>(Pope Michael I), (1990present) elected in<space/><link><target>Kansas</target></link>, USA.<extension extension_name='ref' name="10 Most Bizarre People on Earth"><template><target>cite web</target><arg name="url">http://www.oddee.com/item_65612.aspx</arg><arg name="title">10 Most Bizarre People on Earth</arg><arg name="work">Oddee</arg><arg name="accessdate">20 August 2015</arg></template></extension></listitem><listitem>Pope of the &quot;True Catholic Church&quot;:<space/><link><target>Lucian Pulvermacher</target></link><space/>(Pope Pius XIII), (19982009), elected in<space/><link><target>Montana</target></link>, USA.</listitem><listitem>Mirko Fabris (Pope Krav I), (19782012), elected in<space/><link><target>Zagreb</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Croatia</target></link>.<extension extension_name='ref'><link type='external' href='http://books.google.com/books?id=LgvvaMgTsZ0C&amp;amp;pg=PT75&amp;amp;dq=%22Victor+von+Pentz%22&amp;amp;hl=en&amp;amp;sa=X&amp;amp;ei=2FSPUbfuF-bD7AbczYH4BA&amp;amp;redir_esc=y'>George D. Chryssides, ''Historical Dictionary of New Religious Movements'' (Rowman &amp; Littlefield 2011 978-0-81087967-6)</link></extension></listitem><listitem>Joaqun Llorens (Pope Alexander IX), (2005present), elected in<space/><link><target>Elx</target></link>, Spain.<extension extension_name='ref'><template><target>cite web</target><arg name="url">http://iglemerci.jimdo.com/</arg><arg name="title">Iglesia Católica Apostólica Española Tradicionalista y Mercedaria - Iglesia Católica Apostólica Española Tradicionalista y Mercedaria</arg><arg name="publisher"></arg><arg name="accessdate">20 August 2015</arg></template></extension></listitem><listitem>Popes of the &quot;<link><target>Iglesia Catlica Apostlica Remanente</target></link>&quot;, based in<space/><link><target>Buenos Aires</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Argentina</target></link>: Oscar Michaelli, elected on 24 March 2006 by a group of 34<space/><link><target>episcopi vagantes</target></link><template><target>citation needed</target><arg name="date">March 2013</arg></template><space/>as Pope Leo XIV. On his death on 14 February 2007, he was succeeded by Juan Bautista Bonetti, who took the name of Pope Innocent XIV, but resigned on 29 May 2007. Alexander IX was chosen in his place.<extension extension_name='ref'><template><target>cite web</target><arg name="url">http://icaremanente.blogspot.com</arg><arg name="title">Iglesia Católica Apostólica Remanente</arg><arg name="author">Iglesia Católica Remanente</arg><arg name="publisher"></arg><arg name="accessdate">20 August 2015</arg></template></extension></listitem></list><heading level='2'>Fiction</heading><paragraph>Antipopes have appeared as fictional characters. These may be either in<space/><link><target>historical fiction</target></link>, as fictional portraits of well-known historical antipopes or as purely imaginary antipopes.</paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Jean Raspail</target></link>'s novel<space/><italics><link><target>l'Anneau du pcheur</target></link></italics><space/>(The Fisherman's Ring), and<space/><link><target>Grard Bavoux</target></link>'s<space/><italics>&quot;Le Porteur de lumire&quot;</italics><space/>(The Light-bringer).<extension extension_name='ref'>Jean Raspail, &quot;L'Anneau du pcheur,&quot; Paris: Albin Michel, 1994. 403 p. ISBN 2-226-07590-9</extension><extension extension_name='ref'>Grard Bavoux, &quot;Le Porteur de lumire,&quot; Paris: Pygmalion, 1996. 329 p. ISBN 2-85704-488-7</extension></listitem><listitem>The fictional synth-pop artist<space/><link><target>Zladko Vladcik</target></link><space/>claims to be &quot;The Anti-Pope&quot; in one of his songs.<extension extension_name='ref'><template><target>cite av media</target><arg name="url">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v</arg><arg name="title">Zladko Vladcik - I am the Antipope</arg><arg name="date">21 January 2007</arg><arg name="work">YouTube</arg><arg name="accessdate">20 August 2015</arg></template></extension></listitem><listitem><link><target>Dan Simmons</target></link>'s novels<space/><italics><link><target>Endymion (Hyperion Cantos)</target><part>Endymion</part></link></italics><space/>and<space/><italics><link><target>Rise of Endymion</target></link></italics><space/>feature a Father Paul Dur who is the routinely murdered antipope Teilhard I. At the end of the last novel, it is mentioned that the person calling himself the pope of the Technocore loyal Catholics is recognized by very few even among those, and he is referred to as an antipope.</listitem><listitem><link><target>Ralph McInerny</target></link>'s novel<space/><italics>The Red Hat</italics><space/>features a schism between liberals and conservatives following the election of a conservative African Pope; the liberal faction elect an Italian cardinal who calls himself &quot;Pius XIII&quot;.</listitem><listitem>In the video game<space/><italics><link><target>Crusader Kings II</target></link></italics><space/>by Swedish developer<space/><link><target>Paradox Interactive</target></link>, the player may appoint one of their bishops as an antipope.</listitem></list><heading level='2'>See also</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>List of tombs of antipopes</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>List of popes</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Avignon Papacy</target></link></listitem></list><heading level='2'>References</heading><paragraph><template><target>Reflist</target></template></paragraph><heading level='2'>External links and bibliography</heading><paragraph><template><target>Wiktionary</target><arg>antipope</arg></template></paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem><link type='external' href='http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/01582a.htm'>''Catholic Encyclopedia'': &quot;Antipope&quot;</link></listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/28501/antipope'>''Encyclopdia Britannica'': &quot;Antipope&quot;</link></listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='http://media.isnet.org/kristen/Ensiklopedia/AntiPope.html'>''The Pope Encyclopaedia'': &quot;Antipope&quot;</link></listitem><listitem>Kelly, J.N.D,<space/><italics>The Oxford Dictionary of Popes</italics>,<space/><link><target>Oxford University Press</target></link>, USA (1 June 1986), ISBN 0-19-213964-9.</listitem><listitem>Raspail, Jean,<space/><italics>'L'Anneau du pcheur</italics>, Paris: Albin Michel, 1994. 403 pp.&amp;nbsp;ISBN 2-226-07590-9.</listitem><listitem>Bavoux, Grard,<space/><italics>Le Porteur de lumire</italics>, Paris: Pygmalion, 1996. 329 pp ISBN 2-85704-488-7.</listitem></list><paragraph><template><target>Antipopes</target></template></paragraph><paragraph><template><target>Use dmy dates</target><arg name="date">June 2013</arg></template></paragraph><paragraph><link><target>Category:Antipopes</target><part></part></link><link><target>Category:Ecclesiastical titles</target></link><link><target>Category:History of the papacy</target></link><link><target>Category:Lists of Roman Catholic popes</target></link><link><target>Category:Schisms in Christianity</target></link></paragraph></arti